<TEXT>
soviet president mikhail s 
gorbachev sets out from his first superpower summit meeting with 
president bush to lead his warsaw pact alliance into a new era of 
cooperation with the west or risk being left behind and alone 
as he and bush parted after two days in the mediterranean 
gorbachev headed home for a meeting with a dramatically different 
and more westwardlooking warsaw pact leadership than when members 
last convened in july 
the communist bloc alliance has become less communist and less a 
bloc presenting gorbachev with the challenge of leading the 
transition he described from a kremlindominated military alliance 
to a new political association guiding east europe in its rush to 
erase the lines that have divided east and west for 45 years 
culturally and geographically moscows warsaw pact partners are 
closer to the west than the vast soviet union straddling europe and 
asia and as they turn away from the kremlin to face the west 
gorbachev may find it increasingly difficult to drive his 
stubbornly backward society at a quick enough pace to catch up 
at his joint news conference with bush closing their first 
summit meeting gorbachev declared himself encouraged and 
inspired by the changes that have swept hardline communists from 
power in poland east germany czechoslovakia and bulgaria 
the changes he said show the desire of these peoples to 
ennoble their societies to make them more democratic and 
humanitarian and to open up to the rest of the world 
but they also dramatically alter the kremlins once dominant and 
domineering role in the alliance 
for the first time since the pact was signed in the polish 
capital in 1955 in response to the formation of the north atlantic 
treaty alliance one of the leaders present polish prime minister 
tadeusz mazowiecki will be a noncommunist 
mazowiecki a leader of the independent solidarity labor 
movement suppressed with soviet support in 1981 was elected in 
august to head east europes first noncommunist government in four 
decades 
and on the eve of the summit the leadership of east germany at 
the heart of the strategic alliance was wrenched by its second 
spasm in recent weeks as communist leader egon krenz and the 
partys entire top echelon abdicated to a 25member panel of 
reformers in a desperate effort to salvage some measure of support 
for the communist party 
krenz relinquished the party post he had held less than six 
weeks and although he retained the largely ceremonial title of 
president it was not immediately clear who would represent east 
germany at the moscow meeting 
several other east european leaders including petar mladenov of 
bulgaria and karel urbanek of czechoslovakia are attending their 
first warsaw pact leadership meeting 
and for the first time since the alliance was formed the head 
of the polish communist party now out of power apparently wasnt 
invited at all 
nicolae ceausescu who continues to rule romania with the iron 
hand once rewarded by moscow is the only east bloc leader who 
rejects the democratically inspired reform movement with the 
recent fall of orthodox communist leaders like erich honecker in 
east germany and milos jakes in czechoslovakia he is likely to 
find himself more isolated than ever as he sits down with the new 
generation of east european leaders 
