soil erosion from water runoff declined 
between 1982 and 1987 but wind damage to the nations cropland 
increased slightly an agriculture department report said today 
the latest national resources inventory released by the 
departments soil conservation service said sheet and rill 
erosion by water dropped to an average of 38 tons per acre 
annually from 43 tons during the fiveyear period 
wind erosion however increased 01 ton per acre to 33 tons 
per acre annually most wind erosion of cropland is concentrated in 
the great plains states 
total sheetandrill erosion of cropland was reported at 16 
billion tons per year and wind erosion at nearly 14 billion tons 
annually 
the national summary of the nri a benchmark reference used 
widely by government and private conservationists and others will 
be followed next year by a complete report officials said 
wilson scaling chief of the soil conservation service said the 
report includes information on erosion cropland use irrigation 
tillage and conservation needs 
the area of rural nonfederal land totals 14 billion acres the 
report said of this 4228 million acres are cropland 4017 
million rangeland 3945 million forestland and 599 million in 
minor land uses 
from 1982 to 1987 it said 4 million acres of rural nonfederal 
land were converted to urban and transportation uses which include 
roads and airports 
cropland increased 14 million acres in the five years to 4228 
million from 4214 million while pastureland declined 23 million 
acres and rangeland dropped 6 million acres 
