<TEXT>
hospital patients face a greater risk of 
infection or inappropriate surgery because many hospitals arent 
meeting quality standards according to the head of a group that 
monitors healthcare facilities 
more than a third of us hospitals failed to meet quality 
standards designed to guard against inappropriate surgery 
unnecessary blood transfusions and poorly coordinated treatment in 
special coronary and intensivecare units according to a report in 
sundays chicago tribune 
the report also found that more than 40 percent of hospitals 
were cited for violations of safety standards ranging from 
inadequate electrical wiring to improper disposal of hazardous 
waste 
the report was based on surveys of 5208 facilities collected 
from 1986 to 1988 by the joint commission on accreditation of 
healthcare organizations which sets quality standards for 
healthcare facilities 
the chicagobased commission said it had not analyzed the data 
to determine how many violations were major 
but the commissions president dr dennis oleary said 
compliance problems mean that there is a greater risk of a bad 
outcome such as infection in the hospital or a transfusion 
reaction or a surgical misadventure 
we consider that to be serious he said 
oleary said more and more hospitals are letting their buildings 
run down because of financial pressures do hospitals have 
adequate resources to really comply with the standards maybe 
not oleary said 
the tribune reported that the commission found that 
fiftyone percent of hospitals did not have adequate procedures 
for reviewing surgery to determine whether it should have been done 
and whether it was done correctly 
fiftysix percent did not properly monitor and evaluate how 
well the medical staff in different departments gave care 
fifty percent did not properly monitor what happened to 
patients in special intensivecare and coronarycare units 
thirtyfive percent did not always review blood transfusion 
procedures to determine whether a patient needed a transfusion and 
whether whole blood or blood components should have been used 
blood components carry less risk of infection from viruses that 
cannot be detected by current screening tests such as hepatitis c 
about fivesixths of the nations hospitals are surveyed by the 
joint commission whose seal of approval qualifies them to get 
medicare and medicaid reimbursements without an extra government 
inspection 
barry bader a quality consultant based in rockville md said 
the pattern of problems indicated that physicians are increasingly 
reluctant to review each others care in the hospital either 
because of the time required or the fear of lawsuits 
that doesnt mean patients are getting poor care only that 
hospitals often are uninformed about what kind of care they are 
giving bader said 
dr sidney wolfe director of the washington dcbased public 
citizen health research group said the commission should publicly 
disclose its compliance data for individual hospitals 
if youre going to be a regulatory agency you have to let the 
public know what youre finding wolfe said 
