<TEXT>
the supreme court today agreed to hear 
arguments favoring states rights and consider limiting the federal 
governments power to control water used by hydroelectric dams 
the court said it will hear a california appeal supported by 
more than 40 states 
the waterrights dispute pits the federal energy regulatory 
commission against californias water resources control board the 
bush administration sided with the federal commission and 
environmentalists supported the state agency 
the commission in 1983 licensed construction of a hydroelectric 
power project on rock creek a small tributary of the american 
river near placerville calif 
the dams owner rock creek limited partnership plans to 
generate electric power and sell it to pacific gas amp electric co 
the state water resources agency sought to limit the flow of 
water over the dam by requiring that enough water continue flowing 
in rock creek to assure survival of trout 
but the federal commission in 1987 said it has exclusive control 
over how much water should flow over the dam 
the 9th us circuit court of appeals ruled in favor of 
commission last june saying the federal power act strongly 
suggests that congress intended to vest final authority for the 
regulation of hyrdroelectric power projects in federal hands 
the appeals court said that interpretation of the law is 
supported by a 1946 supreme court ruling which it said gave states 
control over water distribution only for limited purposes for 
irrigation and city water supplies 
congress intended federal law to preempt state regulation in 
all aspects of hydropower projects save for the limited proprietary 
exceptions specified in the law the appeals court said 
permitting the state to limit water supplied to the dam could 
jeopardize the economic feasibility of the project and undermine 
the federal licensing authority the 9th circuit court added 
californias appeal was supported by a friendofthecourt legal 
brief signed by the attorneys general of 43 other states the only 
states not signing were maryland new york virginia louisiana 
ohio and wisconsin 
the 43 states said the appeals court ruling if adopted 
nationwide would fundamentally alter state control of water 
resources and eviscerate comprehensive state regulatory systems for 
allocating water 
leading environmental groups including the national audubon 
society and the sierra club said illconceived hyrdroelectric 
development should not be shielded from state regulation 
but administration lawyers urged the justices to reject any call 
for what they said would be unworkable dual control over 
hydroelectric projects 
the case is california vs ferc 89333 
</TEXT>
