<TEXT>
prime minister margaret thatcher faces reelection 
as conservative party leader tuesday and for the first time since 
she got the job 14 years ago she has a challenger 
sir anthony meyer a rankandfile legislator little known 
outside parliament doesnt expect to win but he hopes to get 
enough votes to send mrs thatcher a message of discontent at a 
time of 73 percent inflation and difficulties over britains place 
in europe 
former defense secretary george younger mrs thatchers 
campaign manager said monday that out of the 374 conservative 
members of parliament eligible to cast ballots he expected up to 
20 will vote for meyer 
some are expected to abstain in a show of disapproval of mrs 
thatchers sometimes autocratic leadership style and her 
reluctance to accept some of the new rules dictated by britains 
membership in the european economic community 
tory lawmaker christopher hawkins says estimates of 
antithatcher votes and abstentions range from 23 to 66 with an 
average prediction of 45 
fortyfive would do mrs thatcher little harm analysts agree it 
would take 100 or more to wound her and no one expects her to lose 
outright early guesses are tricky because many members have 
refused to state their preference before they put their votes in 
the ballot box 
the waverers face a dilemma they want to send her a message 
but not such an overwhelming one that she will feel obliged to 
resign 
conservative lawmakers vote annually on their leader and mrs 
thatcher 64 has been endorsed without opposition since 1975 when 
she ousted former prime minister ted heath 
she has led the conservative to three successive election 
victories since 1979 become the longestserving british prime 
minister this century and said she wants to go on and on 
but public opinion polls show she is the least popular prime 
minister this century her tories are up to 15 points behind the 
opposition labor party and her sweeping economic and social 
reforms have gone too far for many voters 
while the rich have become richer in the past 10 years the 
poor have become poorer said meyer a 69yearold former 
diplomat who represents a welsh constituency and has always been on 
the liberal antithatcher wing of the party 
there is a real limit on the extent to which the electorate is 
prepared to tolerate public squalor whether in filthy streets 
worsening public transport or inadequate schools or hospitals in 
return for private affluence he said monday 
younger said in a weekend television interview that meyer 
wrongly believes there is a vast groundswell who want him to do 
this im afraid the truth is there isnt and people mostly would 
very much wish he hadnt 
to be reelected on the first ballot mrs thatcher needs 57 
percent of the 374 eligible votes a majority plus 15 percent if 
she fails up to two more ballots can be held until a winner 
emerges on a simply majority of 188 votes 
the victor becomes party leader and prime minister subject only 
to the formality of royal approval 
the conservatives hold 375 of the 650 seats in the house of 
commons but speaker bernard weatherill does not vote 
mrs thatcher who has a vote said last week the leadership 
vote was bad for britain and for the party but she defended 
meyers democratic right to challenge her 
opinion polls consistently have named another former defense 
secretary michael heseltine as the person voters would most like 
to replace mrs thatcher 
meyer has said he mounted the challenge not in any hope of 
winning but as a way of enticing more likely candidates into the 
race 
however heseltine has repeatedly said he wont participate in 
the campaign to unseat mrs thatcher although he has not indicated 
whether he will cast a ballot or abstain tuesday 
</TEXT>
