<TEXT>
the supreme court said monday it will decide 
whether the federal governments delays in setting cleanair 
guidelines limit its power to fine polluters 
the justices said they will hear an appeal by general motors 
which faces fines of up to 25000 a day for violating airquality 
standards at a massachusetts carassembly plant 
a lower court rejected gms claims that it should be shielded 
from fines because of federal delays on proposed revisions in state 
pollution controls 
the public should not be penalized with dirtier air because of 
what often are unavoidable delays by the federal environmental 
protection agency the 1st us circuit court of appeals ruled 
in other action the court 
agreed to consider limiting the federal governments power to 
control water used by hydroelectric dams the court said it will 
hear a california appeal supported by more than 40 states 
refused to enhance the power of states and their citizens to 
block shipments of hazardous waste from other states the court 
rejected an appeal by alabama officials who failed to prevent 
shipments of hazardous waste from an abandoned texas chemical 
refinery 
agreed to decide whether us banks with branch offices 
overseas must pay depositors after foreign governments seize or 
freeze those accounts the court will review a ruling that required 
citibank to pay depositors 
robert h bork whose supreme court nomination was defeated by 
the senate in 1987 is representing citibank 
left intact a victory for rock star prince by refusing to 
revive a copyrightinfringement claim by his halfsister over the 
hit song u got the look 
the airpollution case involves a gm plant in framingham mass 
and focuses on the joint federalstate system for cleaning up the 
atmosphere 
under the federal clean air act the epa sets national air 
quality standards and states must adopt plans to meet those 
standards 
the epa in 1980 approved a massachusetts plan for reducing 
pollution from paint at autoassembly factories the plan required 
car makers to comply fully with the federal rules by dec 31 1985 
but epa officials extended the deadline for any plant switching 
from lacquer to enamel paints which emit less pollutants 
gm initially planned to stay with lacquer at the framingham 
factory but in june 1985 announced it would convert to enamel paint 
by the summer of 1987 gm asked that it not be required to comply 
with the dec 31 1985 standards until 20 months later 
massachusetts officials approved gms proposal and submitted a 
revised plan to the epa on dec 30 1985 
without waiting for federal approval gm began building a 200 
million plant in framingham to use enamelbased paints while 
continuing to operate its existing factory 
epa officials went to federal court in august 1987 seeking fines 
of up to 25000 a day against gm for 20 months of airquality 
violations at the old plant but it was not until september 1988 
that the epa rejected the stateapproved pollutioncontrol system 
at the new plant 
a federal judge barred the epa from fining gm for violations of 
the dec 31 1985 standards ruling that the federal agency itself 
violated the clean air act by taking more than four months to rule 
on the stateapproved plan submitted dec 30 1985 
but the 1st circuit court last june said the epas failure to 
meet the fourmonth deadline does not disqualify it from fining 
companies that violate previously approved pollutioncontrol rules 
the appeals court told the trial judge to decide how much the 
fines should be advising him to consider whether the epas delay 
was reasonable and what impact the delay had on gm 
the us chamber of commerce joined gm in urging the supreme 
court to review the dispute 
chamber of commerce lawyers said the 1st circuit court ruling 
invites unfair treatment for businesses the bush administration 
said the 1st circuit court ruling was correct 
</TEXT>
