president bush and soviet leader 
mikhail gorbachev are finding it easier to endorse political change 
in europe than to deal with the consequences 
after a summit meeting in which both leaders envisioned an end 
to eastwest rivalry they face the considerably more difficult 
task of redefining their respective military alliances without 
upsetting a balance of power established through 40 years of cold 
war 
for gorbachev the assignment is especially tricky he seeks to 
preserve his warsaw pact alliance at the same time that its 
hardline communist regimes are being swept aside during the 
postsummit news conference a czechoslovakian journalist pointedly 
asked whether he had renounced the brezhnev doctrine used to 
justify the 1968 soviet invasion of that country as it began to tip 
westward 
every nation is an independent entity in world politics and 
every people has the right to choose its own destiny the destiny 
