<TEXT>
the federal government has granted hundreds of 
airline pilots medical exemptions to fly but has not used similar 
exemptions to allow pilots to fly past the mandatory retirement age 
of 60 a congressional study released monday said 
rep edward r roybal dcalif who released the general 
accounting office study said the study reveals an inconsistency in 
federal aviation administration rules that he said have kept some 
of the most qualified and experienced pilots from operating large 
commercial airliners 
the report says the faa granted 1301 exemptions to requirements 
for medical certificates 1960 through 1988 it said that among the 
40000 active air transport pilots 605 now have special 
issuance medical certificates for alcoholism and 104 for 
cardiovascular conditions 
allowing such pilots to continue flying but excluding a 
60yearold pilot in perfect health clearly does not make sense 
said roybal the chairman of the house committee on aging 
the report said none of 67 petitions by 418 pilots asking for 
exemptions for pilots over 60 has been granted by the faa which 
has said it adopted the rule for safety some of the applications 
are still pending 
pilots over 60 can fly commercial jets with fewer than 30 
passengers and a payload under 7500 pounds but must retire as 
captains or copilots of large airliners 
roybal said the faa should reconsider the basis for its age60 
rule which went into effect in 1959 and has been challenged by 
pilot groups and others over the years 
the report by the gao which is congress investigative arm 
summarized legal challenges to the rule legislative efforts and 
the position of the faa and pilots but made no recommendation 
the air line pilots association representing pilots earlier 
opposed the rule but since 1980 has backed the faa position saying 
there has been no study that provides a way of determining which 
pilots over 60 are fit to fly safely 
opponents of the rule include the aircraft owners and pilots 
association and the national business aircraft association 
</TEXT>
