<TEXT>
church leaders monday called on religious 
individuals and organizations to provide nonjudgmental and 
compassionate care and support to people suffering from aids 
the leaders also called on churches to develop accurate and 
comprehensive aids education materials in a context that promotes 
individual selfesteem teaches the fundamental goodness of human 
sexuality and supports the integrity of responsible and caring 
intimate relationships 
the comments were included in a consensus statement on 
appropriate religious responses to the aids epidemic adopted monday 
by about 130 clergy and lay leaders from christian jewish 
unitarian and interfaith groups during a conference at the carter 
presidential center 
the religious community has a responsibility to assure that 
all whose lives are affected by the epidemic will have access to 
compassion nonjudgmental care respect support and assistance 
the statement said 
the right rev douglas e theuner chairman of the joint 
commission on aids and bishop of the episcopal diocese of new 
hampshire said church leaders must overcome a perception among 
aids sufferers that religious people view the disease as the 
wraith of god for an immoral lifestyle 
some think that the religious community believes aids is a 
judgment of god but by and large the religious community does not 
and those of us in a position of leadership need to convey that 
more forcefully he said 
the consensus statement said churches have a responsibility to 
transform public attitudes and policies so that adequate care and 
appropriate preventative measures will be available for all people 
in need 
the group called on president bush to demonstrate moral and 
political leadership by protecting people with aids from 
discrimination by expanding drugtreatment programs to all who 
choose them by expediting the experimental treatment approval 
process by expanding homecare programs for aids sufferers and by 
encouraging strict confidentiality of aids tests 
the statement said foreigners should be allowed to visit or 
become citizens of the united states if they are eligible to do so 
regardless of whether they have aids 
the group also advocated comprehensive programs for drug users 
including the distribution of aids prevention information and 
materials including bleach for the sterilization of hypodermic 
needles 
aids acquired immune deficiency syndrome is a deadly disease 
which attacks the bodys immune system crippling its ability to 
ward off infections that are not a problem for most people such as 
a rare pneumonia and a rare skin cancer 
the latest federal public health figures indicate 112241 people 
have been reported with aids since 1981 and 59 percent of them have 
die from it no one is known to have recovered 
sixty percent of the total cases have involved homosexual or 
bisexual males 20 percent were intravenous drug abusers and 
another 7 percent were both drug abusers who were also homosexual 
males fortythree percent of all cases involved minorities 
in a reference to those statistics the group said in its 
consensus statement that because barriers among us based on 
religion race class gender and sexual orientation that continue 
to generate fear persecution and violence are intensified by the 
aids epidemic we call upon all sectors of our society 
particularly our faith communities to adopt as highest priority 
the elimination of racism classism sexism and homophobia 
the conference was cosponsored by the aids national interfaith 
network the atlanta interfaith aids network and the carter center 
of emory university 
among the groups represented were the evangelical lutheran 
church in america the african methodist episcopal church the 
united synagogue of america the union of american hebrew 
congregations the unitarian universalist association the baptist 
general convention of texas the universal fellowship of 
metropolitan community churches the united methodist church the 
united church of christ the roman catholic church and the 
episcopal church 
