<TEXT>
a new high school soon to open in the suburbs of 
new york city reflects the growing japanese presence in america 
the aim of the school is to prepare japanese children for college 
back in their home country there are some decided differences in 
the way students are drilled in japan and the united states 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
east will meet west on the campus of keio 
high school an experimental academy that will teach the children 
of japanese executives posted in america 
the school on the grounds of manhattanville college in this 
suburb of new york city is scheduled to open in september 1990 
construction of a classroom and administrative building a 
gymnasium cafeteria and dormitories began in the fall 
keio was conceived as a way to attract japanese businesses to 
new york state but it is now seen as an important educational 
effort in its own right an experiment in bilingual bicultural 
education that could help expand the horizons of education in japan 
and in the united states 
the school is a bellwether for the state if not the 
country says j edward meyer the regional representative on the 
new york board of regents the states educational policy board 
it could become an instant model 
the catalyst for the creation of the school was concern about 
the education of the children of the growing number of japanese 
businessmen who work in america an estimated 20000 to 30000 live 
in the northeast alone the most in any area of north america 
yasumitsu nihei who will be principal of the new school says 
the average stay of the japanese businessman once was about five 
years but now theyre staying longer and the needs of their 
collegebound children are more important 
most japanese children want to attend a university in their 
homeland to be mainstream in japan says nihei in many cases 
workers stay with a single company all their lives and to get into 
that company they must get into the right school he says 
but to get into the university students must pass an 
examination all of their previous education from the second grade 
on is geared toward drilling them with the facts necessary to pass 
that test they attend school eight hours a day 5 days a week 
240 days a year 
by comparison american students attend six hours a day five 
days a week for about 180 days a year and american schools 
concentrate less on the rote memorization that is commonplace at 
japanese schools 
there is an elementary school based on the japanese system in 
new york city but until recently high school students often were 
sent home to japan 
the meiji gakuin university of tokyo plans to open a traditional 
japanese high school in sweetwater tenn where 70 japaneseowned 
companies including nissan sharp and matsushita have operations 
meanwhile terry lynam a spokesman for gov mario cuomo said 
new yorks department of economic development had seized on the 
establishment of a school to help japanese businessmen already here 
and attract more 
tokyos prestigious keio university was consulted matilda 
cuomo the governors wife even visited the university during 
negotiations 
they settled on manhattanville as the site of the new school 
because it was close to new york city and because manhattanville 
has a sister school in japan the university of the sacred heart 
half the faculty in the new school will be american and the 
curriculum will cull the best from the american school system 
particularly an emphasis on writing which is more american than 
japanese 
the curriculum will meet graduation requirements of both new 
york and japan and an outstanding student at the school would be 
assured entry into keio university without the dreaded exam 
while it is expected that japanese students will make up most of 
the student body american students will not be excluded 
entrance into the school will be based on an exam grades 
bilingual ability demonstrated in written essays letters of 
recommendation and extracurricular activities 
the school will operate on two semesters and will accommodate 
both the japanese school year which runs april to march and the 
us school year tuition is projected at 12000 a year room and 
board at 4000 
manhattanville president marcia savage said students from her 
school will studentteach at the school or work in labs there 
dr paul valenti superintendent of harrison schools is also 
looking forward to a partnership with his asian neighbor 
in his district 67 percent of the districts 2166 students 
are asian mostly japanese but only 24 students in the harrison 
high school system are asian 
harrison currently offers a bilingual program for japanese 
students at its parsons elementary school 
its an opportunity for us to share programs for both of us 
to learn valenti says some of our japanese students prefer 
the american experience and want to go to an american university 
keio university which is investing 40 million in the school 
including 95 million to buy 27 acres of the manhattanville 
campus feels the experiment could pay dividends at home 
japan is in an age of internationalization says nihei who 
hopes the schools success will lead to similar programs elsewhere 
in the united states 
</TEXT>
