<TEXT>
its hard to imagine devoting ones life to 
penetrating the forbidding walls of a prison and trying to reach 
the hearts of convicts but this michigan woman does it and her 
message is i am me and i am good cuz god dont make junk 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
people think these boys are just 
throwaways that theyre getting what they deserve i think the 
public needs to know that god is behind prison walls 
thats the feeling of gloria simmons who with accordion and 
bible in hand walks through prison doors each sunday to try to 
inspire even the most hardened inmates 
in a drafty room once used as a barracks for prisoners the spry 
grandmother of two stands before about 100 uniformed inmates at 
camp sauble the states only bootcampstyle corrections facility 
my heart is behind the prison doors with you she says to 
the men most of them repeat offenders under age 25 
after having former drill instructors bark orders in their face 
all week many of the young men crack a smile for the first time 
since the previous sunday 
when i first came here i didnt want to go to church 
services says inmate christopher parker 19 of dowagiac who 
was sent to camp sauble on a breaking and entering conviction 
but when you see her it brings your spirits up and makes you 
feel better for the rest of the week 
im glad my mom made me take accordion lessons because its 
opened quite a lot of prison doors simmons says with a chuckle 
one of her hymns she wrote herself and it sums up her message 
i am me and i am good cuz god dont make junk 
simmons began her mostly musical church services at camp sauble 
in 1984 two years after she took early retirement from a 17year 
career as a case worker with the michigan department of social 
services 
when shes not at camp sauble on sunday simmons can be found at 
other michigan prisons she plays monthly at the minimumsecurity 
prison at cassidy lake near ann arbor and at the kinross 
mediumsecurity facility in the upper peninsula 
shes also a regular visitor at several other prisons including 
camps cusino and ojibway in the upper peninsula and camps pellston 
pugsley and waterloo in the lower peninsula 
attendance at simmons services usually runs a remarkable 98 
percent compared with about 10 percent at most prisons across the 
state officials say those who choose not to attend must stay in 
their cells for quiet time most weeks the only inmates not in 
attendance are those who are banned as punishment guards say 
prison officials say simmons services seem to touch many of the 
inmates 
they really put their heart and soul in the services says 
officer john hawkins that sunday service gives them the drive to 
complete the week 
accompanied by her brother on the banjo simmons songs are 
upbeat an inspiration to the offenders who have been given 90 days 
to change their ways if they fail they are sent to a conventional 
prison usually with a much longer sentence 
there are the traditional hymns such as amazing grace and 
within a few minutes nearly every one of the men is clapping and 
singing along in thunderous voices as simmons belts out the tunes 
on her accordion after every song they roar their approval 
a brief christian service follows inmates read along with their 
donated bibles and bow their shaved heads in prayer a guard 
patrols the room 
simmons musical prowess also includes the piano organ and 
guitar in her 20s she sang in an allgirl dance band in lansing 
where she grew up 
besides her commitment to people behind bars simmons deviates 
from the stereotypical grandmother image in other ways she 
recently sold her motorcycle which had earned her the nickname 
motorcycle mama among friends i never had the time to ride 
it she says 
simmons first prison performance came when a fellow male member 
at her assembly of god church who had been playing guitar for 
inmates at camp sauble then a regular minimumsecurity prison 
asked her to fill in one sunday 
it became an addiction she says 
she also began teaching bible class at the prison every tuesday 
it was at those bible classes which eventually grew to 40 
students that she cultivated friendships with about 20 prisoners 
when they were transferred to other state prisons in early 1988 to 
make room for the boot camp simmons began corresponding and 
visiting them all over the state 
they became like family she says some of them have no 
visitors but me many have sent her paintings and small 
prisonmade artifacts 
only about five of the original 20 men remain behind bars and 
many stopped corresponding upon their release simmons says 
that doesnt bother me i had a part of their life while they 
were here but they want to put their past behind them when they 
get out 
simmons doesnt get any money for her prison work but 
emphasizes that she doesnt do it for recognition monetary or 
otherwise 
money would never equal what i get back from these boys she 
says 
</TEXT>
