<TEXT>
the dallas museum of art has put together a major traveling 
exhibit of more than 150 works by 49 black artists of the 20th 
century 
black artancestral legacy the african impulse in 
africanamerican art opened dec 3 and will run through feb 25 
before moving on to the high musuem in atlanta the milwaukee art 
museum and the virginia museum of fine arts in richmond 
the importance of african cultural traditions to the creativity 
of black artists in the united states jamaica haiti and the 
bahamas is the focus of the exhibit 
unlike the american and european modernists who borrowed the 
forms of primitive african sculpture early in the 20th century 
africanamerican artists tapped into the wellspring of their 
ancestral art to produce a new synthesis of the african and the 
american said richard r bretell director of the museum 
when an africanamerican artist makes use of snake imagery of 
woven patterns or of repetititve images derived from dance he is 
not merely borrowing forms but making a powerful statement about 
cultural continuity 
the exhibit features works by such artists as richmond barthe 
xenobia bailey sargent johnson ed love john biggers and derek 
webster 
