<TEXT>
visitors who visit idaho during its 1990 
centennial have a unique opportunity to experience the theme that 
runs through the states history like a vein of gold mans love 
affair with the land 
the gem states 100th birthday party will feature a gamut of 
wild west celebrations in virtually every town and county and 
there is the added reward of traveling through eyecatching idaho 
idaho became the 43rd state on july 3 1890 
settlers traveled to idaho for its resources gold and silver 
endless stands of timber the rich volcanic soil 
people who came here were looking for something to exploit 
but not in the bad sense said arthur hart a member of the idaho 
centennial commission who spent 17 years as director of the idaho 
historical society 
one of the most involved projects in the celebration is the 
creation of a centennial park state officials insisted that 
monument reflect industrys role in opening up the wild territory 
to civilization 
mining attracted the first major influx of settlers so it was 
natural to locate the park around the old gold rush towns of custer 
and bonanza in central idaho 
those rustic ghost towns are a short jaunt off idaho 75 nestled 
in the pines along the yankee fork of the salmon river ore wagons 
rattled along the motorway toll road to the ranching community of 
challis where the parks interpretive center will be built 
we had two oregon trail parks but we didnt have any park for 
mining which brought them here in the first place hart said 
the oregon trail people passed through idaho but didnt think 
they could farm here 
within two hours drive from the centennial park are the granite 
crags of the sawtooth mountains the champagne whitewater of the 
middle and main forks of the salmon or the worldclass ski slopes 
of sun valley the resort retains the 1940s aura that attracted the 
worlds elite ernest hemingway gary cooper and clark gable to 
name a few 
the silver valley in the idaho panhandle historically has ranked 
as one of the top 10 mining districts in the world 
travelers intending to put in a busy day can visit the coeur 
dalene district mining museum in wallace idahos oldest standing 
building in the catholic cataldo mission built in 1853 or the 
lakeside resort community of coeur dalene 
cataldo was built by jesuit priests and local indians using 
wooden pegs instead of nails 
north americas longest gondola will soon stretch from the town 
of kellogg to the silverhorn ski area in the silver valley 
northern idaho remains a thick carpet of timber and once 
featured the largest stand of white pine in the world lumberjacks 
used to transport logs on the clearwater river to the sawmills of 
lewiston in gigantic wooden flotillas complete with tents for 
cooking and sleeping 
lumberjacks will chop saw and climb trees as lewiston showcases 
its logging heritage with the grand finals of the world association 
of timber sports in may 1990 
people from all races came to idaho to work the mines farm or 
build the railroads the centennial honors them all with 
celebrations or interpretive studies 
in the midst of world war ii in 1942 9400 japaneseamericans 
were relocated to the windswept minidoka relocation center near 
twin falls in southcentral idaho 
the japanese american citizens league plans to build an 
interpretive center at the camp 
basques from the spanish pyrenees migrated to the united states 
from the 1800s on to tend sheep bands boise is the largest enclave 
of basques in north america they plan their second jaialdi 
cultural festival in boise in june 1990 drawing basques from the 
west and europe 
when american explorers meriwether lewis and william clark 
passed into idaho through lolo pass in 1805 they met friendly 
shoshone and nez perce indian tribes who had roamed through 
northern idaho on spotted appaloosa horses for centuries 
they are two of the states six tribes that will meet for the 
first time in boise on july 915 for an all idaho indian expo 
to present their histories dreams and social issues 
the idaho centennial calendar lists more than 500 events next 
year from an idaho cowboy poetry gathering to a whistle stop tour 
of union pacific railroads steam engine no 8444 idahos 
statehood day celebration will run 43 hours from july 2 to 
independence day with a dizzying schedule of fireworks and parades 
former gov john evans said i want a celebration of one 
million meaning he wanted every man woman and child involved 
hart said were coming as close to that as we can 
</TEXT>
