<DOCNO> AP891204-0225 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the first tune the children of 
spruga seem to learn is that of the klaxons of the yellow postbuses 
that wind their way through the mountains above locarno at the 
northern end of lake maggiore in switzerlands ticino 
a child on his tricycle pedals fast toward a stranger and stops 
just short of a collision he sings out like a klaxon and pedals 
off another child restless on her mothers lap echoes the klaxon 
warning of the bus as it rounds a series of tight curves 
spruga indemini and their fellow communities wrapped high into 
the alps above locarno and lugano or tucked into the river valleys 
are groupings of gray stone houses with heavylooking gray slate 
roofs the gray cobbled streets are often stairs all look as if 
they had been and would be there forever geraniums and other 
flowers add a blast of color woods and pastures are all around and 
much of the year a sound heard even more frequently than that of 
the klaxon is that of cowbells 
at the foot of the mountains lie lake maggiore and locarno with 
palm and fig trees oleanders and flowers and accessible lakefront 
there are restaurants galore an old town and a lido on market 
day booths along its main street sell everything from kitchen 
utensils to raincoats to jewelry made in india the long arcade 
along the street is a sort of permanent market sneakers and 
scarves toys and teddy bears and food of all kinds including 
almonds that a smiling old lady dips in hot caramel 
the arcade is a splendid shelter on a rainy day locarno famous 
for its sunshine does have rain too another indoor spot 
demanding a visit is the museum in the castello visconteo a 
centuriesold restored castle whose exhibits range from jean arps 
paintings to roman glass bronzes and other artifacts from the 
first century 
as one dines at the trattoria da luigi takes the funicular to 
the shrine of the madonna del sasso or the lake boats to muralto 
luino and the like one sinks into the feeling of being in italy 
the names the flowers the sun the blue water the stuccoed 
buildings in pink and cream suggest the mediterranean but it is 
switzerland though the swiss didnt get hold of it for keeps until 
the 16th century locarno was a commercial crossroads and military 
base under the romans who called the predominantly celtic people 
they found there the helvetii julius caesar defeated them in the 
gallic wars and then made allies of them 
locarno also was the scene in 1925 of an international 
conference including france britain germany and a number of other 
nations that drew up a series of mutual guarantees known as the 
locarno pact supposed to create a spirit of peace and goodwill 
britains foreign secretary at the time austen chamberlain was a 
key figure at the meeting adolf hitler denounced the pact in 1936 
and remilitarized the rhineland chamberlains halfbrother 
neville later british prime minister signed another more 
notorious peace pact with hitler in 1938 at munich with similar 
results with czechoslovakia as the pawn 
but the average visitor to locarno lake maggiore and its sister 
lake lugano will probably save historical research for another 
time concentrating instead on the lake boats and the mountains 
heading south from locarno he soon will truly be in italy on the 
way he can stop at switzerlands brissago isles where a botanical 
garden has plants from subtropical regions all over the world 
australia china north africa the americas the mediterranean 
this is just a foretaste of whats waiting at the south end of the 
lake on italys borromeo islands owned since the early 16th 
century by the borromeo family prominent rich and devout 
charles borromeo who died in 1584 was canonized 
the garden at isola madre with its bitter orange mimosa 
egyptian papyrus and banana trees has five terraces and a palace 
relatively modest by 18th century palatial standards white and 
bluegreen peacocks stroll the lawns and pheasants are almost under 
foot 
on isola bella the gardens are more elaborate ten terraces 
surmounted by a multistoried sculpture with niches containing 
figures and sculpted scallop shells statues are silhouetted 
against the sky atop the whole thing is the sculpted family 
symbol a unicorn its baroque beautiful and blatant the 
enormous palace one guidebook quotes french author gustave 
flaubert as saying it could have accommodated 2000 people is on a 
par with the gardens there are a weapons and armor room a 
tapestry gallery a room where napoleon and his family stayed as 
guests and three theaters including a hell theater with 
marionettes symbolizing the environment and a twopipe organ to 
produce lugubrious sounds 
lying between isola bella and isola madre is isola dei 
pescatori a longtime fishing village which has narrow streets and 
stone houses but also a heavy overlay of tourists and vendors 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

