<TEXT>
battle lines in congress are already being 
drawn over whether and how to spend the money the bush 
administration plans to slice off next years pentagon budget 
on one side are lawmakers who say liberalization in eastern 
europe means the defense cuts should be large and who want to use 
the money to beef up education child care and other domestic 
programs that have been pinched in recent years 
if the tearing down of the berlin wall means nothing more than 
we put the uss missouri in mothballs we will not have accomplished 
much says liberal rep george miller dcalif 
arrayed against them are others who want to use the savings to 
reduce the 1991 deficit to 64 billion a goal universally seen as 
difficult yet one that is required by the grammrudman 
balancedbudget law 
there seems hardly any room for discussion that the 
defense savings go to anything but deficit reduction says sen 
pete domenici rnm ranking republican on the senate budget 
committee 
dangling somewhere in between are senators and representatives 
who will be wary of defense cuts that affect military bases or 
contractors in their home districts 
the light bulb in their heads says jobs says ellen 
nissenbaum a lobbyist for programs for lowincome people 
while congress just finished its 1990 budget work on nov 22 
the administration is already sketching out its spending blueprint 
for fiscal 1991 which begins next oct 1 that document will be 
presented to congress on jan 22 
defense secretary dick cheney is reportedly preparing budget 
plans that will pare up to 180 billion from planned pentagon 
spending through 1994 
even if carried to the maximum such cuts would reap little 
savings next year because of the nature of defense spending 
in any given year much of it is carried over from previous 
commitments such as an aircraft carrier on which construction 
began two years ago or is contained in difficulttobreak 
longterm contracts stretching into the future even laying off 
troops brings with it offsetting expenses such as retirement 
payments unemployment benefits and other costs 
because of that the consensus among lawmakers and lobbyists is 
the reductions are likely to rein military spending by no more than 
3 billion to 8 billion next year out of a nearly 300 billion 
pentagon budget the entire federal budget will be about 12 
trillion 
such savings are but a tiny fraction of the 40 billion that 
many on capitol hill expect will be needed to shave the 1991 
deficit to the grammrudman target of 64 billion 
the peace dividend isnt large and there are a lot of 
claimants says rep bill frenzel rminn ranking republican on 
the house budget committee 
although the defense buildup of the early reagan administration 
years left a lasting public impression of an evergrowing pentagon 
the military budget has shrunk over the last five years when the 
effects of inflation are considered 
the trend was considered likely to continue in 1991 even before 
cheney began considering reductions and eastern european countries 
began asserting more political independence from the soviet bloc 
house minority leader bob michel rill predicted a feeding 
frenzy last week by lawmakers eager to cut defense spending if 
the administration asks for a budget reduction 
but theres little question that the nations defense system 
its bases and the companies that supply the weapons food and other 
goods for them has a large base of support in congress 
even so the need for deficitreduction is likely to lead 
lawmakers to take a bite out of the military budget the fight over 
reaching the grammrudman deficit target is likely to also focus on 
elements that have been contested in recent budget years higher 
taxes which bush opposes and domestic cuts which democrats 
reject 
a responsible budget approach has to be balanced says rep 
leon panetta dcalif house budget committee chairman who has 
issued similar calls in the past with limited success 
