<TEXT>
united arab emirates oil minister mana 
said otaiba said monday his country was ready to limit its oil 
output but not to the extent demanded by the organization of 
petroleum exporting countries 
otaiba said the united arab emirates was willing to reduce its 
current output which he put at 26 million barrels a day to under 
2 million during the first half of 1990 
but he stressed it would not accept a quota of 1094 million 
barrels a day assigned under an opec pact reached last week 
he said the united arab emirates was willing to limit production 
to under 2 million barrels a day if the other opec nations abide by 
their quotas 
the 13 opec members agreed last week to set their output ceiling 
at 22 million barrels a day it left the quota for the united arab 
emirates which has not complied with its opec quota over the past 
two years unchanged 
otaiba also said he expects demand for opec crude to exceed 23 
million barrels a day in 1990 higher than the groups own demand 
estimates 
he said continued economic growth should keep demand strong 
moreover recent upheaval in eastern europe could help spur demand 
by touching off new economic growth there he said 
