<TEXT>
the justice departments antitrust division 
monday recommended approval of a partial merger of the two daily 
newspapers in las vegas under a joint operating agreement 
assistant attorney general james f rill recommended that the 
las vegas sun and the las vegas review journal dailies be allowed 
to combine commercial and production facilities but continue to 
publish separate editions 
rill found that because of circulation and advertising losses 
the las vegas sun was in probable danger of financial failure 
and therefore qualified for the antitrust exemption granted by the 
newspaper preservation act 
under the law attorney general dick thornburgh must make the 
final decision whether to allow the proposed joint operating 
agreement to proceed 
if the agreement becomes effective las vegas would be the 21st 
city where daily newspapers operate under such an arrangement 
rills report said that financial records show that the morning 
las vegas sun has lost 13 million since 1981 as a result of a 
substantial decline in circulation and advertising in recent years 
circulation of the sun has shrunk from 58000 in 1982 to 52000 
last year while advertising linage has dropped from 2 million 
column inches in 1984 to 13 million in 1988 the divisions report 
said 
during the same period the circulation of the allday las vegas 
reviewjournal has increased from 93000 in 1982 to more than 
130000 last year 
the reviewjournals advertising linage has gone up from 29 
million column inches in 1984 to nearly 31 million inches in 1988 
the report said 
the reviewjournal which is owned by donrey inc holds a 
commanding lead in the las vegas daily newspaper advertising 
market over the sun which is owned by the family of its founder 
the late hank greenspun 
